<div class="flex flex-col gap-5">
	<p>
		Alice Bucknell started with Scotland. Not as a metaphor, but as a geological fact. A NASA researcher told them that Martian topsoil most closely resembles the soil of the Scottish Highlands. That sent them down a path that eventually produced a language belonging to both places and neither.
	</p>
	<p>
		The Isle of Skye has a Martian festival every summer. A small Scottish community called Glenelg has twinned itself with a point of the same name on Mars. Scottish Gaelic is dying in the specific way languages die when more people can read them than speak them. A script without a voice.
	</p>
	<p>
		That's where they found their materials. Scottish Gaelic on one side. On the other, the Martian alphabet devised by Hélène Smith, a French mystic who hosted salons in 19th-century Paris where she would channel what she called Martian intelligence and transcribe its language. Smith's alphabet has 18 letters. Scottish Gaelic also has 18. The conlang Bucknell built from these two systems runs on Python. Feed it an English sentence and it converts it into a blend of a dying Earth language and channeled alien script. The model has a persistent memory. The same word always translates the same way.
	</p>
	<p>
		Once they had the written component, they built the sonic one. Eighteen sounds from Martian wind recorded by rovers. Eighteen sounds from Arctic acoustics. Each letter triggers its corresponding sound from whichever place it came from. The result is a language that takes minutes to speak a single paragraph. Sprawling and durational, rolling over the listener without asking to be understood.
	</p>
	<p>
		The political argument underneath is about terra nullius, the colonial legal fiction that declares a place empty and therefore available. The Arctic and Mars are both read through that lens. Territories without history, without intelligence, without life worth accounting for. Building a language for these places is a refusal. The language isn't meant for you. It speaks for itself and to itself. Whether you're there doesn't really matter.
	</p>
	<p>
		Bucknell is working against the demystifying impulse that runs through most AI language work. The assumption that if we build the right model, we'll finally crack the code of whatever we don't understand yet. They want remystification instead. The same technologies used to render the world legible turned toward making something that resists legibility on purpose.
	</p>
	<p>Portrait by Zein Majali, courtesy the artist.</p>
</div>
